{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17647075","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17647075"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:40:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:40:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18228"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18228","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18228"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.09,0.43,0.04,0.3]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10942"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79202"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10942","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10942"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18228"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64554"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"10203"},{"type":"tags","id":"10207"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25430"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25432"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79202","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79202"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 58-year-old male was investigated by his GP for chronic lower back pain with no known trauma prior. Clinical examination illicited tenderness at the lumbar spine. His lumbar X-ray showed compression fractures at L4 and L5. His ALP was raised.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following metabolic bone diseases is characterised by excessive osteoclastic bone resorption and chaotic bone formation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Rickets and osteomalacia","Hyperparathyroidism","Paget\u0027s disease","Fibrous dysplasia","Osteopetrosis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPaget\u0027s disease\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by excessive osteoclastic bone resorption followed by disorganised osteoblastic bone formation, leading to structurally weak and deformed bones. The disease often presents most frequently as an incidental finding on radiographs or on biochemistry.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERickets and osteomalacia\u003C/strong\u003E are due to defective mineralisation of bone, due to vitamin D deficiency, and do not involve excessive bone resorption or chaotic bone formation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHyperparathyroidism\u003C/strong\u003E leads to increased osteoclastic activity and bone resorption but does not result in the chaotic bone formation seen in Paget\u0027s disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFibrous dysplasia\u003C/strong\u003E is a developmental disorder where normal bone is replaced by fibrous tissue, leading to bone deformities, but does not involve the excessive resorption and chaotic formation seen in Paget\u0027s disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOsteopetrosis\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by defective osteoclastic resorption, leading to abnormally dense but brittle bones, which is the opposite of the process seen in Paget\u0027s disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Paget\u0027s disease of bone is characterised by excessive osteoclastic activity followed by disorganised osteoblastic bone formation.","The resulting bone in Paget\u0027s disease is structurally weak and prone to deformities and fractures.","Paget\u0027s disease often presents with bone pain, deformities, and elevated alkaline phosphatase levels."],"references":["Uday S, H\u00f6gler W. Nutritional rickets \u0026 osteomalacia: A practical approach to management. Indian J Med Res. 2020 Oct;152(4):356-367. doi: 10.4103/ijmr.IJMR_1961_19. PMID: 33380700; PMCID: PMC8061584.","Uday S, H\u00f6gler W. Nutritional Rickets and Osteomalacia in the Twenty-first Century: Revised Concepts, Public Health, and Prevention Strategies. Curr Osteoporos Rep. 2017 Aug;15(4):293-302. doi: 10.1007/s11914-017-0383-y. Erratum in: Curr Osteoporos Rep. 2017 Oct;15(5):507. doi: 10.1007/s11914-017-0395-7. PMID: 28612338; PMCID: PMC5532418.","Khurana, I., Khurana, A., \u0026 Kowlgi, N. G. (2019). Textbook of Medical Physiology_-E-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Clarke B. Normal bone anatomy and physiology. Clin J Am Soc Nephrol. 2008 Nov;3 Suppl 3(Suppl 3):S131-9. doi: 10.2215/CJN.04151206. PMID: 18988698; PMCID: PMC3152283","Florencio-Silva R, Sasso GR, Sasso-Cerri E, Sim\u00f5es MJ, Cerri PS. Biology of Bone Tissue: Structure, Function, and Factors That Influence Bone Cells. Biomed Res Int. 2015;2015:421746. doi: 10.1155/2015/421746. Epub 2015 Jul 13. PMID: 26247020; PMCID: PMC4515490"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64554"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18228"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64554","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64554"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-13T17:32:23+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-13T17:32:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10942"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79202"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemC